ce to everyone interested in Roman drama or literature more generally, comparative literature or drama and theatre studies. This contextual approach has the potential of changing the way in which Roman drama is viewed.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aLatin dramaxHistory and criticism. 4aDrama. 4aRoman literature. 4acomedy. 4atragedy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aFrangoulidis, Stavros, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarrison, Stephen J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aManuwald, Gesine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2016z9783110485097oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831104555880 cprintz978311045557140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311045650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110456509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110456509.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016